<br>
As an aside, and for those who might be technical purists, this thread is an example of the Fallacy of Composition - an erroneous reasoning of part ot whole. In other words, the idea that the actions of one person may be accurrately ascribed to every member of their social circle is a fallacy of composition as it ascribes the actions of one to the actions of all in a blanket fashion.<br>
<br>
Another fun fallacy we see here is the Fallacy of Shifting the Burden of Proof. Any person making an accusation assumes the burden of proof by virtue of making the accusation. When said accuser finds his task to weighty to prove, the easy way is to attempt to fallaciously attempt to shift the burden of proof to his opponent. And example of this would be...<br>
<br>
Person A makes wildly improbable accusation against person B<br>
Person B refutes it handily.<br>
Person A responds with the line &quot;Well, it's quite obvious that I'm right, and if you disagree, prove me wrong!&quot;<br>
<br>
We won't even go into specifics or the various other Fallacies of Equivocation seen here, but your friend will no doubt find some enjoyment picking out the many lovely examples of argument gone horribly awry.<br>
<br>
(Still I agree with the idea of guilt by association in the singular aspect that a truly distasteful action by a guildmate would certainly give me pause to question my continued membership should the officer cadre not respond) <p>a_Bearhat01<BR>
and <BR>
